## Finding: Beta Graduation Criteria Are Completely Absent

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: The six Beta phase skills (email_templates, error_boundaries, feature_flags, feedback_system, product_analytics, rate_limiting) collectively implement useful capabilities, but none defines or enforces what constitutes successful Beta completion. A Beta phase without objective exit criteria is not a phase — it is an indefinite holding pattern. First-principles analysis: a Beta must have defined success gates (error rate thresholds, retention minimums, latency SLAs, user satisfaction scores, adoption metrics) before it can graduate to GA. None of the six skills specifies these gates. The feature_flags skill has a rollout table (1%→10%→50%→100%) but no criteria for when to advance. The product_analytics skill has funnel templates but no defined threshold that constitutes "Beta passed." The feedback_system collects reports but has no resolution-rate graduation gate.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill `beta_graduation_criteria` (Phase 5.75): Defines measurable exit gates — error rate < X%, P0 feedback resolution rate ≥ Y%, 7-day retention ≥ Z%, p95 API latency < Nms, at least M users from at least K organizations completing core activation funnel, zero open P0 bugs. Trigger: "define beta exit criteria", "beta graduation checklist", "GA readiness assessment."
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without this, Phase 6 (Handoff) has no signal that Beta is actually done. Phase 6 skills (user_documentation, feature_walkthrough) assume a stable, complete product — they inherit debt if Beta was never formally closed. Disaster recovery (Phase 6) SLAs cannot be defined without knowing the GA quality bar.

