## Finding: A/B Testing Has No Statistical Rigor Framework

### Gap Type: SHALLOW_COVERAGE
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: The feature_flags skill mentions A/B testing and recommends "at least 1,000 users per variant" and "statistical significance" before deciding, but provides zero implementation of statistical significance testing. No p-value calculation, no power analysis, no minimum detectable effect (MDE) guidance, no sample size calculator reference, no stopping rules (to prevent peeking bias), no Bayesian alternative. The product_analytics skill tracks conversion events but has no methodology for determining whether observed differences are real or noise. A team following these skills could run an A/B test for two weeks, see a 3% lift, declare it a win, and be completely wrong 40% of the time due to underpowered tests or early stopping.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill `ab_testing_rigor` (Phase 5.75): Provides a pre-experiment checklist (hypothesis, primary metric, MDE, required sample size via formula or calculator), a during-experiment protocol (no peeking rule, Bonferroni correction for multiple metrics), and a post-experiment decision tree (statistical significance check, practical significance check, segment analysis). Includes worked examples with real numbers. Trigger: "validate A/B test results", "experiment design", "statistical significance check."
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 6 community_management and user_documentation will describe features that won A/B tests — if those wins were false positives, the docs describe the wrong thing. Product analytics dashboards (5.75) will show misleading conversion data.

