## Finding: Email Deliverability Monitoring Is Absent

### Gap Type: SHALLOW_COVERAGE
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: The email_templates skill configures SPF/DKIM/DMARC DNS records (good) and uses Resend (good), but provides zero monitoring of actual deliverability: no bounce rate tracking, no spam complaint rate tracking, no domain reputation monitoring, no delivery webhook processing from Resend. Resend provides webhooks for email.bounced, email.complained, email.delivered events. Without processing these, a degraded sending domain could silently cause all emails to land in spam for weeks. Industry standard: bounce rate > 2% or spam rate > 0.1% triggers sending domain suspension. The skill also has no email queue with retry logic — if Resend is temporarily down, the current fire-and-forget send() returns null and the email is lost forever.
### Proposed Resolution: Extend email_templates skill OR create `email_observability` skill (Phase 5.75): Resend webhook handler for delivery events, bounce/complaint rate tracking in database, alerting when bounce > 1% or complaint > 0.08%, email retry queue using Bull/BullMQ, and dead-letter queue for permanently failed sends. Trigger: "monitor email deliverability", "email bounce tracking", "email queue setup."
### Cross-Phase Impact: Lost emails during Beta (password resets, team invitations) are the most common cause of user abandonment. Phase 6 user_documentation will describe email flows that silently don't work for some users. disaster_recovery has no Email Service runbook for silent deliverability failure (only for provider outages).

================================================================

## Finding: Privacy Consent and Data Processing Agreement for Beta Are Missing

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: The product_analytics skill mentions GDPR opt-in/opt-out for PostHog and "store email consent timestamp" in the email_templates compliance section, but there is no skill covering the full consent management infrastructure required before running a Beta with real users: cookie consent banners (GDPR Article 6), explicit analytics consent capture and storage, beta participant data processing agreements (DPA), right-to-erasure workflows covering PostHog data, right-to-access for collected feedback, data retention policies for beta feedback data. Running a Beta that collects product analytics and feedback without a compliant consent flow exposes the project to GDPR enforcement. Under GDPR, collecting behavioral analytics without consent is a violation even during Beta with small user numbers.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill `privacy_consent_management` (Phase 5.75 or cross-cutting): Cookie/consent banner component, consent storage in database with timestamps and version, PostHog opt-in/opt-out tied to consent, right-to-erasure endpoint that deletes user data from PostHog AND feedback database, DPA template for beta participants. Trigger: "GDPR consent", "cookie banner", "privacy compliance", "right to erasure."
### Cross-Phase Impact: Directly feeds Phase 6 (Handoff) community_management legal posture and user_documentation privacy section. Retroactively invalidates all product analytics data collected without consent.

