## Finding: Load Testing at Beta Scale Has No Coverage

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: The rate_limiting skill protects against individual user abuse but has no concept of load testing to discover where the system breaks under Beta-scale concurrent load. The 5.5-Alpha qa_playbook has a "performance spot-check" (manual, 5 cases) but no load test. Before a Beta with any meaningful user count, the team needs to know: what is the maximum concurrent users before p95 latency exceeds 500ms? What is the database connection pool exhaustion point? What happens to rate-limit Redis when it is under load? Which endpoints are the bottlenecks? The disaster_recovery skill references load testing in its prevention section for Scenario 8 (performance degradation) but no skill provides the actual load testing methodology or tooling.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill `load_testing` (Phase 5.75): k6 or Artillery script templates for the core user journeys (login → dashboard → primary action → API call), guidance on ramping profiles (steady state vs. spike), acceptance criteria (p95 < 500ms, p99 < 2s, error rate < 0.1% at target RPS), database connection pool sizing guidance, and Redis capacity planning for rate-limit storage. Trigger: "load test the API", "performance testing", "stress test before beta."
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without load testing, Beta will discover performance problems in production under user load, generating P0/P1 feedback that overwhelms the feedback_system. Phase 6 disaster_recovery SLAs (SEV1 recovery time targets) cannot be set without knowing actual system capacity.

