## Finding: Industry Deviation — DORA Metrics Are Not Defined or Tracked for Beta Phase

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: DORA (DevOps Research and Assessment) defines four key metrics for high-performing software teams: Deployment Frequency, Lead Time for Changes, Change Failure Rate, and Mean Time to Recovery (MTTR). None of the six Beta skills define, track, or reference these metrics. The product_analytics skill tracks user behavior; it does not track engineering delivery metrics. The error_tracking skill (Alpha, upstream) captures errors but does not compute Change Failure Rate (percentage of deployments causing a production incident). The feedback_system tracks user-reported bugs but not deployment-triggered regressions. Industry standard: teams graduating from Beta to GA should demonstrate Elite DORA performance (deployment frequency: multiple times/day, lead time: < 1 hour, change failure rate: < 5%, MTTR: < 1 hour). Without tracking these, Beta graduation has no engineering performance benchmark.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill or addition to beta_graduation_criteria (Loop 1 proposed): DORA metrics tracking setup — deployment frequency via CI/CD pipeline event logging, lead time from PR open to production via GitHub API, change failure rate via correlation of deployments with error spikes in Sentry, MTTR via incident open-to-close timestamps. Target: reach Elite tier before GA graduation. Trigger: "track DORA metrics", "engineering performance metrics."
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 6 disaster_recovery runbooks include MTTR targets (30 min for backend outage, 15 min for frontend rollback) — but without MTTR tracking in Beta, there is no baseline. Phase 7 (Maintenance) presumably monitors these metrics; Beta should establish them.

================================================================

## Finding: Industry Deviation — SOC2 Trust Criteria Are Unaddressed for Beta With Real User Data

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: SOC2 Type I/II compliance is increasingly required for B2B SaaS, especially when handling business data during a Beta that may include paying customers. SOC2's five Trust Service Criteria (Security, Availability, Processing Integrity, Confidentiality, Privacy) map directly to Beta phase activities: Security — covered partially by Phase 4 skills; Availability — no SLA defined (Loop 5 Finding); Processing Integrity — no data validation skill; Confidentiality — no DLP controls; Privacy — partially covered by analytics consent (Loop 5 Finding). The rate_limiting skill enforces availability indirectly, but no skill defines or tracks uptime percentage, no skill implements audit logging for all data access (required for SOC2 CC7), and no skill covers the evidence collection process needed for SOC2 readiness. Beta with enterprise customers who contractually require SOC2 cannot proceed without this foundation.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill `soc2_readiness_beta` (Phase 5.75) or addition to compliance_validation_beta (Loop 4 proposed): SOC2 control mapping for Beta phase — audit log table (who accessed what data, when), uptime tracking, incident log with timeline evidence, change management record (feature flag changes logged), access control review. Not a full SOC2 implementation, but a readiness foundation that makes future SOC2 audit achievable. Trigger: "SOC2 readiness", "audit logging", "compliance controls."
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 6 community_management will engage enterprise prospects who ask "are you SOC2 compliant?" Without audit logging foundations laid in Beta, the answer is no — which blocks enterprise sales. The disaster_recovery skill's security breach scenario (Scenario 6) references audit logs as an investigation tool, but no skill creates them.

