## Finding: Industry Deviation — SRE Error Budgets Not Defined for Beta

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: Google's SRE practices define error budgets: if a service's SLO is 99.9% uptime, the error budget is 0.1% downtime per month (~43 minutes). When the error budget is exhausted, new feature deployments stop until reliability is restored. Phase 5.75-Beta has no SLO definition, no error budget calculation, and no mechanism to halt deployments when reliability is degraded. The rate_limiting skill protects against abuse but not against self-inflicted reliability degradation from frequent Beta deployments. The error_tracking skill (Alpha) sends Sentry alerts, but there is no aggregation of error rate into an error budget that gates further Beta feature releases. Industry standard for Beta phases with real users: define a relaxed SLO (e.g., 99.5%), track error budget consumption, and enforce a deployment freeze when budget is 50% exhausted.
### Proposed Resolution: Add to beta_graduation_criteria (Loop 1 proposed) or create `slo_error_budget` skill: SLO definition template (uptime %, error rate %, latency p95), error budget calculation, budget burn rate monitoring (PostHog or custom dashboard), deployment gate (CI check that blocks deployment if error budget is < X% remaining). Trigger: "define error budget", "SLO tracking", "deployment gate on reliability."
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 6 disaster_recovery defines recovery time targets without knowing the SLO baseline. Phase 7 Maintenance presumably operates against SLOs established in earlier phases — Beta should establish them.

================================================================

## Finding: Industry Deviation — CIS Benchmark Hardening Not Applied to Beta Infrastructure

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: CIS (Center for Internet Security) Benchmarks define hardening standards for cloud infrastructure, container runtimes, and Kubernetes clusters. The Phase 5.75-Beta skills assume the backend runs somewhere (Railway/Render/Docker/k8s) but no skill verifies CIS Level 1 controls are applied to the hosting environment before real Beta users access it. Specific gaps: the rate_limiting skill configures Redis for throttle storage but does not specify that Redis must have authentication enabled (`requirepass`) and TLS in transit — CIS Redis Benchmark requirement. The email_templates skill's Resend configuration does not mention that RESEND_API_KEY must have IP allowlist restrictions if the hosting provider supports them. PostHog's Personal API Key (phx_...) is a write-capable secret that should have IP restrictions. No skill in Phase 5.75 performs an infrastructure security posture check before opening Beta to real users.
### Proposed Resolution: Add a "Infrastructure Security Preconditions" section to a Beta readiness skill (beta_readiness_check proposed Loop 3): Redis auth enabled, Redis TLS in transit, all third-party API keys have minimum necessary scopes, API keys with IP allowlist where provider supports it, TLS 1.2+ enforced on all endpoints, HTTP security headers (HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options) verified. Reference CIS Benchmark Level 1 as the standard. Trigger: "security hardening check", "beta infrastructure audit."
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (Secure) presumably covered application-level security. Beta introduces new third-party integrations (PostHog, Resend, Redis) that each have their own hardening requirements. Phase 6 disaster_recovery Scenario 6 (Security Breach) requires prior hardening to be meaningful.

================================================================

## Finding: Industry Deviation — OWASP API Security Top 10 Not Validated for New Beta APIs

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: Phase 5.75-Beta introduces several new API endpoints: POST /feedback (file upload, multipart), GET/PATCH /feedback (admin operations), and rate-limit-exempt webhooks. OWASP API Security Top 10 (2023) specifically calls out: API1 (Broken Object Level Authorization) — the feedback GET endpoint returns all feedback without filtering by organization, meaning User A can read User B's feedback if they know the ID; API3 (Broken Object Property Level Authorization) — the PATCH /feedback endpoint's UpdateFeedbackDto exposes adminNotes and assignedTo to all authenticated users, not just admins; API4 (Unrestricted Resource Consumption) — the screenshot upload in the feedback POST has no explicit file size limit in the controller, only browser-side validation. The rate_limiting skill applies throttling but not payload size limits. API8 (Security Misconfiguration) — the @SkipThrottle() on webhooks means any endpoint mistakenly decorated with this is permanently unprotected. These are concrete, exploitable gaps in the Beta's new APIs.
### Proposed Resolution: Extend feedback_system skill with: org-scoped GET /feedback query (add orgId filter), admin-only guard on PATCH /feedback (role check), server-side file size limit in the NestJS FileInterceptor (limits: { fileSize: 5 * 1024 * 1024 }). Extend rate_limiting skill with a warning about @SkipThrottle() abuse and a recommendation to use an allowlist pattern instead of decorator-based exemptions. Trigger: "OWASP API security check", "feedback API security review."
### Cross-Phase Impact: API1 (Broken Object Level Authorization) in the feedback endpoint means any beta user can read all other users' feedback, including internal team notes — a privacy violation. This would be a P0 finding in a Phase 4 security audit, but since the feedback_system was added in Phase 5.75 after the security phase, it is not covered.

